GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 661
Short Title: Building Industry Efficiency Act of 2025. (Public)
Sponsors: Representatives Brody, Bell, Cunningham, and Zenger (Primary Sponsors).
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Housing and Development, if favorable, Finance, if favorable, Rules, Calendar,
and Operations of the House
April 2, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO AMEND VARIOUS LAWS TO PROVIDE ADDITIONAL BUILDING
3 INDUSTRY EFFICIENCY.
4 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
5
6 PART I. LOCAL DEVELOPMENT AND CONSTRUCTION REGULATION
7
8 PROHIBIT INSPECTION DEPARTMENTS FROM CHARGING FEES FOR CERTAIN
9 INSPECTION CANCELLATIONS
10 SECTION 1.1. G.S. 160D-1104 is amended by adding a new subsection to read:
11 "(d2) An inspection department shall not charge the permit holder a fee or fail an inspection
12 of a building or structure subject to the North Carolina Residential Code, if the permit holder
13 cancels a scheduled inspection more than one business day before the scheduled inspection."
14
15 LIMIT DESIGN METHODOLOGY AND CONSTRUCTION STANDARDS FOR
16 CERTAIN MUNICIPAL STREETS
17 SECTION 1.2.(a) Article 15 of Chapter 160D of the General Statutes is amended by
18 adding a new section to read:
19 "§ 160D-1502. Limit street design methodology and construction standards for certain
20 municipal streets.
21 Notwithstanding G.S. 136-66.4, municipalities shall not implement design methodology and
22 construction standards for new streets and highways to be accepted by a municipality, utilizing
23 funds that are not wholly municipal funds, that are more stringent than design methodology and
24 construction standards utilized by the North Carolina Department of Transportation. Nothing in
25 this section limits the authority of the North Carolina Department of Transportation to regulate
26 street connections to a public system as authorized by law."
27 SECTION 1.2.(b) This section becomes effective July 1, 2025, and applies to
28 projects initiated on or after that date.
29
30 LIMIT DESIGN METHODOLOGY AND CONSTRUCTION STANDARDS FOR
31 CERTAIN PRIVATE STREETS
32 SECTION 1.3.(a) Article 15 of Chapter 160D of the General Statutes is amended by
33 adding a new section to read:
*H661-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 "§ 160D-1503. Limit street design methodology and construction standards for certain
2 private streets.
3 Municipalities shall not implement design methodology and construction standards for new
4 streets designated as private, and intended to remain privately owned after construction, that are
5 more stringent than design methodology and construction standards utilized by the North
6 Carolina Department of Transportation. Notwithstanding any design methodology and
7 construction standards implemented by the municipality, the municipality must accept
8 engineered street design methodology and construction standards that do not meet minimum
9 standards utilized by the North Carolina Department of Transportation if the engineered street
10 design methodology and construction standards are signed and sealed by a duly licensed
11 professional engineer, under Chapter 89C of the General Statutes, and meet vehicular traffic and
12 fire apparatus access requirements. If engineered street design methodology and construction
13 standards do not meet minimum standards utilized by the North Carolina Department of
14 Transportation, the developer must include disclosures to prospective buyers as outlined in
15 G.S. 136-102.6(f) prior to entering into any agreement or any conveyance with any prospective
16 buyer. A local government is discharged and released from any liabilities, duties, and
17 responsibilities imposed by this Chapter, or in common law, from any claim arising out of, or
18 attributed to, the plan review or acceptance of signed and sealed engineered street design
19 methodology and construction standards submitted pursuant to this section. Nothing in this
20 section limits the authority of local governments or the North Carolina Department of
21 Transportation to regulate private road, driveway, or street connection to a public system, or to
22 regulate transportation and utilities as otherwise authorized by law."
23 SECTION 1.3.(b) This section becomes effective July 1, 2025, and applies to
24 projects initiated on or after that date.
25
26 MUNICIPALITIES REQUIRING DEVELOPERS TO CONSTRUCT CERTAIN
27 PEDESTRIAN FACILITIES AND STREET IMPROVEMENTS TO ACCEPT THOSE
28 IMPROVEMENTS
29 SECTION 1.4.(a) Article 15 of Chapter 160D of the General Statutes is amended by
30 adding a new section to read:
31 "§ 160D-1504. Municipal requirements for pedestrian facilities and street improvements
32 within extraterritorial jurisdiction.
33 A municipality that requires a developer to construct a pedestrian facility or street
34 improvement within public right-of-way located outside of a construction project boundary shall
35 accept that pedestrian facility and street improvement into its municipal public road system for
36 maintenance and repair upon project completion. This section applies to projects located within
37 an extraterritorial jurisdiction of a municipality, established pursuant to Article 2 of Chapter
38 160D of the General Statutes. This section does not apply to public right-of-way that is under the
39 control of the North Carolina Department of Transportation."
40 SECTION 1.4.(b) This section becomes effective July 1, 2025, and applies to
41 projects initiated on or after that date.
42
43 COUNTIES REQUIRING DEVELOPERS TO CONSTRUCT CERTAIN PEDESTRIAN
44 AND STREET IMPROVEMENTS MUST SEEK AGREEMENTS TO ACCEPT THOSE
45 IMPROVEMENTS INTO A PUBLIC ROAD SYSTEM
46 SECTION 1.5.(a) Article 15 of Chapter 160D of the General Statutes is amended by
47 adding a new section to read:
48 "§ 160D-1505. County requirements for pedestrian facilities and public road
49 improvements.
50 A county shall not require a developer to construct a pedestrian facility or public road
51 improvement within public right-of-way located outside of a construction project boundary
Page 2 House Bill 661-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 unless the county obtains an agreement with either the North Carolina Department of
2 Transportation or the municipality, as applicable, that the pedestrian facility or public road
3 improvement will be accepted into a public road system for maintenance and repair. This section
4 applies to projects located within a planning and development regulation jurisdiction of a county,
5 established pursuant to Article 2 of Chapter 160D of the General Statutes. This section does not
6 apply to public right-of-way that is under the control of the North Carolina Department of
7 Transportation."
8 SECTION 1.5.(b) This section becomes effective July 1, 2025, and applies to
9 projects initiated on or after that date.
