19 SECTION 2.2.(i) G.S. 160D-1207(a) reads as rewritten:
20 "(a) Except as provided in subsection (b) of this section, the inspection department may
21 make periodic inspections only when there is reasonable cause to believe that unsafe, unsanitary,
22 or otherwise hazardous or unlawful conditions may exist in a residential building or structure.
23 However, when the inspection department determines that a safety hazard exists in one of the
24 dwelling units within a multifamily building, which in the opinion of the inspector poses an
25 immediate threat to the occupant, the inspection department may inspect, in the absence of a
26 specific complaint and actual knowledge of the unsafe condition, additional dwelling units in the
27 multifamily building to determine if that same safety hazard exists. For purposes of this section,
28 the term "reasonable cause" means any of the following: (i) the landlord or owner has a history
29 of more than two verified violations of the housing ordinances or codes within a 12-month period,
30 (ii) there has been a complaint that substandard conditions exist within the building or there has
31 been a request that the building be inspected, (iii) the inspection department has actual knowledge
32 of an unsafe condition within the building, or (iv) violations of the local ordinances or codes are
33 visible from the outside of the property. In conducting inspections authorized under this section,
34 the inspection department shall not discriminate between single-family and multifamily buildings
35 or between owner-occupied and tenant-occupied buildings. In exercising this power, members
36 of the department shall have a right to enter on any premises within the jurisdiction of the
37 department at all reasonable hours for the purposes of inspection or other enforcement action,
38 upon presentation of proper credentials. Nothing in this section shall be construed to prohibit
39 periodic inspections in accordance with State fire prevention code the North Carolina Fire Code
40 or as otherwise required by State law."
