2 INVESTIGATIVE RECORDS FROM PUBLIC RECORDS
3 SECTION 3.2. Article 2 of Chapter 87 of the General Statutes is amended by adding
4 a new section to read:
5 "§ 87-22.3. Investigation records of the Board.
6 All records, papers, investigative files, investigative notes, reports, other investigative
7 information, and other documents containing information in the possession of or received,
8 gathered, or completed by the Board, its members, staff, employees, attorneys, or consultants as
9 a result of investigations, inquiries, assessments, or interviews conducted in connection with a
10 license application or disciplinary action initiated by the Board, shall not be considered public
11 records within the meaning of Chapter 132 of the General Statutes. Documents described in this
12 section are privileged, confidential, and not subject to discovery, subpoena, or other means of
13 legal compulsion for release to any person other than the Board or its employees or consultants.
14 If any record, paper, or other document containing information collected and compiled by or on
15 behalf of the Board is received and admitted in evidence in any hearing before the Board, the
16 documents shall be a public record within the meaning of Chapter 132 of the General Statutes."
17
18 INCREASE CERTAIN ELECTRICAL CONTRACTOR BOARD EXAMINATION AND
19 LICENSE FEES
20 SECTION 3.3.(a) G.S. 87-44 reads as rewritten:
21 "§ 87-44. Fees; license term.
22 The Board shall collect a fee from each applicant before granting or renewing a license under
23 the provisions of this Article; the annual license fee for the limited classification shall not exceed
24 one hundred dollars ($100.00) one hundred fifty dollars ($150.00) for each principal and each
25 branch place of business; the annual license fee for the intermediate classification shall not
26 exceed one hundred fifty dollars ($150.00) two hundred dollars ($200.00) for each principal and
27 each branch place of business; the annual license fee for the unlimited classification shall not
28 exceed two hundred dollars ($200.00) two hundred fifty dollars ($250.00) for each principal and
29 each branch place of business; and the annual license fee for the special restricted classifications
30 and for the single-family detached residential dwelling license shall not exceed one hundred
31 dollars ($100.00) one hundred fifty dollars ($150.00) for each principal and each branch place of
32 business.
33 The Board shall establish a system for the renewal of licenses with varying expiration dates.
34 However, all licenses issued by the Board shall expire one year after the date of issuance.
35 Licenses shall be renewed by the Board, subject to G.S. 87-44.1 and G.S. 87-47, after receipt and
36 evaluation of a renewal application from a licensee and the payment of the required fee. The
37 application shall be upon a form provided by the Board and shall require such information as the
38 Board may prescribe. Renewal applications and fees shall be due 30 days prior to the license
39 expiration date.
40 Upon failure to renew by the expiration date established by the Board, the license shall be
41 automatically revoked. This license may be reinstated by the Board, subject to G.S. 87-44.1 and
42 G.S. 87-47, upon payment of the license fee, an administrative fee of twenty-five dollars
43 ($25.00), and all fees for the lapsed period during which the person, partnership, firm or
44 corporation engaged in electrical contracting, and, further, upon the satisfaction of such
45 experience requirements during the lapse as the Board may prescribe by rule.
46 The Board may collect fees from applicants for examinations in an amount not to exceed one
47 hundred twenty-five dollars ($125.00), two hundred dollars ($200.00), except the fee for a
48 specially arranged examination shall not exceed two hundred dollars ($200.00). In addition, the
49 Board may collect an examination review fee, not to exceed twenty-five dollars ($25.00), from
50 failed examinees who apply for a supervised review of their failed examinations."
