8 changeout special inspector certificate. To obtain a certificate, a person must pass an
9 examination, as prescribed by the Board, that is based on the North Carolina State Building Code,
10 administrative procedures applicable to permit administration, and relevant topics related to the
11 inspection of residential changeout work as described in G.S. 160D-1106.1. The Board may issue
12 a certificate to each person who successfully applies and completes the examination. The
13 certificate shall bear the signatures of the chair and secretary of the Board.
14 (b) Professional Development Standards for Renewal. – The Board may establish
15 professional development requirements for residential changeout special inspector certificate as
16 a condition of the renewal of their certificates. The purpose of these professional development
17 requirements is to assist in maintaining professional competence. A certificate holder subject to
18 this section shall present evidence to the Board at each certificate renewal after initial certification
19 that during the 12 months before the certificate expiration date, the certificate holder has
20 completed the required number of credit hours in courses approved by the Board. Annual
21 continuing education hour requirements shall be determined by the Board. The Board may, for
22 good cause shown, grant extensions of time to certificate holders to comply with these
23 requirements.
24 (c) Renewal Application. – A residential changeout special inspector certificate must be
25 renewed annually on or before the first day of July.
26 (d) Fee Authorization. – The Board shall establish a schedule of fees to be paid by each
27 applicant for initial certification and renewal certification as a residential changeout special
28 inspector. A fee of not more than twenty dollars ($20.00), as determined by the Board, must be
29 paid by any applicant to the Board for the issuance of an initial certification. A fee of not more
30 than ten dollars ($10.00), as determined by the Board, must be paid by any applicant to the Board
31 for the issuance of a renewal certification. The Board is authorized to charge an extra four dollar
32 ($4.00) late renewal fee for renewal applications made after the first day of July each year.
33 (e) Code-Enforcement Official Exam Waiver. – The Board shall, without requiring an
34 examination, grant a certificate pursuant to this section to any person who, at the time of
35 application, possesses a Building Inspector standard certificate issued by the Board and who is
36 in good standing. The Board may assess a fee for a certificate issued pursuant to this subsection
37 to the extent authorized by subsection (d) of this section for an initial certification.
38 (f) Certification of Licensed Contractors. – The Board shall issue a standard certificate
39 to any person who is currently licensed to practice as a plumbing or heating contractor, licensed
40 pursuant to Article 2 of Chapter 87 of the General Statutes, provided the person successfully
41 completes a short course, as prescribed by the Board, relating to the North Carolina State
42 Building Code and Code enforcement administration.
43 (g) Comity. – The Board may, without requiring an examination, grant a certificate
44 pursuant to this section to any person who, at the time of application, is a similarly certified
45 Building Inspector in good standing by a similar board of another jurisdiction where standards
46 are acceptable to the Board. The certificate granted under this subsection shall expire after one
47 year unless, within that time period, the holder completes a short course, as prescribed by the
48 Board, based on the North Carolina State Building Code and administrative procedures described
49 in subsection (a) of this section. The Board may assess a fee for a certificate issued pursuant to
50 this subsection, to the extent authorized by subsection (d) of this section for an initial
51 certification."
House Bill 661-First Edition Page 27

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 SECTION 4.1.(b) Article 11 of Chapter 160D of the General Statutes is amended
2 by adding a new section to read:
3 "§ 160D-1106.1. Alternate inspection method by residential changeout special inspectors.
4 (a) Notwithstanding the building inspection requirements of this Article, a local
5 government shall accept and approve, without further responsibility to inspect, a residential
6 changeout inspected by a residential changeout special inspector if all of the following conditions
7 are met:
8 (1) The residential changeout is completed by a contractor licensed pursuant to
9 Article 2 of Chapter 87 of the General Statutes, who is different than the
10 residential changeout special inspector charged with inspection of that
11 residential changeout.
12 (2) The new appliance, and related connections, subject to the residential
13 changeout meets all of the following conditions:
14 a. The new appliance requires no alterations to the existing ducting, fuel
15 type, or piping systems other than what is required for transitioning to
16 the new appliance.
17 b. Any venting associated with the new appliance shall be allowed to be
18 installed, replaced, and repaired where such venting does not pass
19 through a rated assembly.
20 c. Any new gas appliance shall be of the same category as the appliance
21 being replaced, if applicable.
22 d. The new appliance does not require relocation, excluding minor
23 adjustments in the same general vicinity.
24 e. The installation of the new appliance does not require the relocation
25 or addition to the existing electrical system, except the replacement of
26 the appliance's branch circuit overcurrent device, or the replacement
27 of the appliance's branch circuit where such circuit does not pass
28 through a rated assembly shall be allowed.
29 f. The electrical branch circuit serving the appliance is single phase.
30 (3) Field inspection of the installation is performed by a residential changeout
31 special inspector, certified pursuant to Article 9C of Chapter 143 of the
32 General Statutes.
33 (4) The residential changeout special inspector provides the local government
34 with a signed written certification that work outlined within subdivisions (1)
35 and (2) of this subsection have been met and is compliant with the North
36 Carolina State Building Code. The certification required under this
37 subdivision shall be provided by electronic or physical delivery, and its receipt
38 shall be promptly acknowledged by the local government through reciprocal
39 means. The certification shall be made on forms created by the Office of the
40 State Fire Marshal, in consultation with the North Carolina Residential Code
41 Council, which shall include the following information:
42 a. Permit number.
43 b. Date of inspection.
44 c. Type of inspection.
45 d. Contractor's name and license number.
46 e. Street address of the job location.
47 f. Name, address, telephone number, and certificate number of the
48 person responsible for the residential changeout special inspection.
49 (b) In accepting certifications of inspections under subsection (a) of this section, a local
50 government shall not require information other than what is required within the certification
51 required under subsection (a) of this section.
Page 28 House Bill 661-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (c) Upon the acceptance and approval of a signed certification by the local government
2 as required under subsection (a) of this section, notwithstanding the issuance of a certificate of
3 compliance, the local government, its inspection department, and its inspectors are discharged
4 and released from any liabilities, duties, and responsibilities imposed by this Article with respect
5 to or in common law from any claim arising out of or attributed to the residential changeout
6 inspection for which the signed written certification was submitted.
7 (d) For the purposes of this section, the phrase "residential changeout" means work
8 requiring a building permit for the purpose of heating and air conditioning appliance and water
9 heater replacement in dwellings subject to the North Carolina Residential Code, and individual
10 residential units of condominiums and apartments provided the individual appliance serves only
11 that residential dwelling unit."
12 SECTION 4.1.(c) By July 1, 2025, the Office of the State Fire Marshal shall develop
13 an internet-based examination and short course as described in G.S. 143-151.24, as enacted by
14 subsection (a) of this section, and make it available on the Office's website for the purpose of
15 certifying residential changeout special inspectors.
16 SECTION 4.1.(d) By July 1, 2025, the Office of the State Fire Marshal shall develop
17 the form required under G.S. 160D-1106.1, as enacted by subsection (b) of this section, and make
18 it available on the Office's website.
