20 PART V. ESTABLISH RIGHT TO REPAIR CONSTRUCTION DEFECTS WITHIN
21 DWELLINGS SUBJECT TO THE NORTH CAROLINA RESIDENTIAL CODE
22 SECTION 5.1.(a) Chapter 87 of the General Statutes is amended by adding a new
23 Article to read:
24 "Article 9.
25 "Right to Repair Construction Defects Act.
26 "§ 87-150. Short title.
27 This Article shall be known and may be cited as the "Right to Repair Construction Defects
28 Act."
29 "§ 87-151. Definitions.
30 The following definitions apply in this Article:
31 (1) Action. – Any civil lawsuit, judicial action, or alternative dispute resolution
32 proceeding for damages or other relief asserting a claim for injury or loss to a
33 dwelling caused by an alleged construction defect arising out of or related to
34 the construction, repairing, or remodeling of the dwelling.
35 (2) Claimant. – An owner who asserts a claim against a general contractor
36 concerning a construction defect in the construction, repairing, or remodeling
37 of a dwelling.
38 (3) Construction defect. – A defect in or a deficiency arising out of the design or
39 construction of improvements, including the use of defective material,
40 products, or components.
41 (4) Dwelling. – A single-family dwelling or other dwelling type subject to the
42 North Carolina Residential Code, including the systems, components, and
43 improvements serving that dwelling.
44 (5) General contractor. – As defined in G.S. 87-1.
45 (6) Serve or service. – Personal service or delivery by certified mail to the last
46 known address of the addressee.
47 "§ 87-152. Notice and opportunity to repair.
48 (a) Notice of Claim. – Before commencing an action against a general contractor
49 regarding a construction defect, the claimant must, no less than 90 days before filing the action,
50 serve a written notice of claim on the general contractor. The notice of claim must contain the
51 following, at a minimum:
House Bill 661-First Edition Page 29

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) A statement that the claimant asserts a construction defect.
2 (2) A description of the claim or claims in reasonable detail sufficient to
3 determine the general nature of the construction defect.
4 (3) A description of any effects of the construction defect, if known.
5 (b) Request for Clarification. – If a notice of claim is not sufficiently stated, the general
6 contractor may advise the claimant within 15 days of service of the notice of claim and request
7 clarification.
8 (c) General Contractor's Response to Notice of Claim. – The general contractor has 30
9 days from service of the notice of claim to inspect, offer to remedy, offer to settle with the
10 claimant, or deny a claim, in whole or in part, regarding the construction defect. The claimant
11 shall receive written notice of the general contractor's election under this section within 30 days.
12 Failure to respond within 30 days is deemed a denial of the claim.
13 (d) Response to General Contractor's Offer. – The claimant shall accept a general
14 contractor's offer, if any, within 10 days of receipt of the offer pursuant to subsection (c) of this
15 section. Failure to respond within 10 days is deemed a denial of the general contractor's offer.
16 (e) Reasonable Access to Dwelling. – If requested, the claimant shall give the general
17 contractor reasonable access to the dwelling at a mutually agreeable time to inspect a construction
18 defect and, if agreed to by the parties, repair a construction defect.
19 (f) Civil Remedy. – Nothing in this Article shall prevent a claimant from proceeding with
20 a civil action or other remedy provided by law if the parties cannot reach a resolution pursuant
21 to this Article.
22 (g) Claimant Repairs. – Nothing in this Article shall be construed to prohibit a claimant
23 from making immediate repairs to an alleged construction defect subject to this Article to protect
24 the health and safety of a dwelling's occupants or to mitigate further damage to the dwelling.
25 (h) Admissibility. – Evidence of offers to settle, repair, or remedy pursuant to this Article
26 is not admissible to prove liability for or invalidity of the claim or its amount.
27 "§ 87-153. Filing a complaint with the Board not prohibited.
28 Nothing in this Article shall prevent a claimant from filing a complaint with the Board in
29 accordance with G.S. 87-11(a1).
30 "§ 87-154. Stay of action.
31 If a claimant files an action in court before first complying with the requirements of this
32 Article, on motion of a party to the action, the court shall stay the action for 120 days and such
33 additional time that is necessary for compliance with the requirements of this Article."
34 SECTION 5.1.(b) This section becomes effective October 1, 2025, and applies to
35 actions commenced on or after that date.
36
37 PART VI. MISCELLANEOUS
38
39 MODIFY PUBLIC POOL LAWS TO CLARIFY PRIVATE POOL EXCLUSION AND
40 TO EXEMPT PUBLIC COLD BATHS
41 SECTION 6.1.(a) G.S. 130A-280, as amended by Section 4.51(a) of S.L. 2024-49,
42 reads as rewritten:
43 "§ 130A-280. Scope.Scope and definitions.
44 (a) This Article Part provides for the regulation of public swimming pools in the State as
45 they may affect the public health and safety. As used in this Article, the term "public swimming
46 pool" means any structure, chamber, or tank containing an artificial body of water used by the
47 public for swimming, diving, wading, recreation, or therapy, together with buildings,
48 appurtenances, and equipment used in connection with the body of water, regardless of whether
49 a fee is charged for its use. The term includes municipal, school, hotel, motel, apartment,
50 boarding house, athletic club, or other membership facility pools and spas, spas operating for
51 display at temporary events, and artificial swimming lagoons. As used in this Article, an
Page 30 House Bill 661-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 "artificial swimming lagoon" means any body of water used for recreational purposes with more
2 than 20,000 square feet of surface area, an artificial liner, and a method of disinfectant that results
3 in a disinfectant residual in the swimming zone that is protective of the public health. This Article
4 Part does not apply to any of the following:
5 (1) A private pool serving a single family dwelling and used only by the residents
6 of the dwelling and their guests.guests regardless of whether their guests gain
7 use of the private pool through a sharing economy platform or pay a fee for
8 its use. In all cases in which a fee is exchanged for access to a private pool
9 serving a single-family dwelling that is used only by the residents of the
10 dwelling and their guests, the private pool shall be maintained in good and
11 safe working order.
12 (2) A private pool serving a single family dwelling meeting the minimum
13 requirements of this subdivision which is offered to, and used by, individuals
14 on a temporary basis utilizing a sharing economy platform. For the purposes
15 of this subdivision, a sharing economy platform means an online platform
16 used to facilitate peer-to-peer transactions to acquire, provide, or share access
17 to goods and services. For the purposes of this subdivision, a pool must meet
18 all of the following minimum requirements:
19 a. Pools must have proper fencing and barriers to prevent unsupervised
20 access, especially by children. The fence should be at least 4 feet high
21 with a self-latching gate.
22 b. Pools must have clear and conspicuous signage posted around the pool
23 area specifying pool rules, depth markers, and any potential hazards.
24 c. Pools must be equipped with basic lifesaving equipment, including life
25 rings and reaching poles.
26 d. Pool decks and surrounding areas must have non-slip surfaces.
27 e. Pools must have properly fitted covers for all submerged suction
28 outlets.
29 f. Pools must be well-maintained with proper chemical balance and
30 cleanliness to ensure safe and healthy swimming conditions.
31 (2a) A public cold bath that meets all of the following requirements:
32 a. Is a tub or tank that is used by the general public, one bather at a time,
33 regardless of whether a fee is charged for its use.
34 b. Contains chilled water that is (i) maintained at a temperature lower
35 than 60 degrees Fahrenheit, (ii) no more than 180 gallons in volume,
36 and (iii) at a depth that allows the bather to maintain the bather's head
37 above the water while in a seated position.
38 c. Continuously filters and sanitizes the chilled water.
39 (3) Therapeutic pools used in physical therapy programs operated by medical
40 facilities licensed by the Department or operated by a licensed physical
41 therapist, nor to therapeutic chambers drained, cleaned, and refilled after each
42 individual use.
43 (b) The following definitions apply in this Part:
44 (1) Artificial swimming lagoon. – Any body of water used for recreational
45 purposes with more than 20,000 square feet of surface area, an artificial liner,
46 and a method of disinfectant that results in a disinfectant residual in the
47 swimming zone that is protective of the public health.
48 (2) Public swimming pool. – Any structure, chamber, or tank containing an
49 artificial body of water used by the public for swimming, diving, wading,
50 recreation, or therapy, together with buildings, appurtenances, and equipment
51 used in connection with the body of water, regardless of whether a fee is
House Bill 661-First Edition Page 31

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 charged for its use. The term includes municipal, school, hotel, motel,
2 apartment, boarding house, athletic club, or other membership facility pools
3 and spas, spas operating for display at temporary events, and artificial
4 swimming lagoons.
5 (3) Sharing economy platform. – An online platform used to facilitate
6 peer-to-peer transactions to acquire, provide, or share access to goods and
7 services."
8 SECTION 6.1.(b) This section becomes effective July 1, 2025.
